{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1774289873,"nonce":"ub4kK88t729cJ2711H1Y5bKGBfQ=","title":"Formal analysis of training method choice (BCS/DAI/PAI-ASF)","message":"## Summary\n\nFormal mathematical and control-theoretic analysis of the three candidate training methods for Part 2 (SISU-conditioned adaptive control). Consolidates findings from independent analyses by Claude Opus and Gemini 3.1 Pro Preview, grounded in Crevecoeur, Cluff, \u0026 Scott (2019) and related robust control theory.\n\n## Background\n\nThe project trains GRU networks to perform reaching under uncertainty, with SISU (Scalar Information about System Uncertainty) as an extra input encoding the current trial's uncertainty level. Three methods have been considered for how SISU maps to perturbation exposure during training.\n\n## Analysis of Methods\n\n### DAI (Direct Amplitude Inference) — REJECTED\n\nSISU = actual perturbation amplitude. Provides complete information about the perturbation, enabling perfect feedforward cancellation (u_cancel = -alpha*B*v + u_nominal). This is adaptive control (gain scheduling), not robust control. Mutual information I(w; SISU) is maximal. Fundamentally misaligned with studying robustness.\n\n### BCS (Balanced Context Switches) — INFERIOR\n\nSISU = binary (perturbed or not). 50% catch trials. When s=1, network cannot predict specific perturbation, but optimization is expected cost over perturbation distribution — LQG-like, not H-infinity-like.\n\nLimitations:\n- Binary signal: two discrete controllers, not a graded continuum\n- s=0 controller has no robustness incentive (knows w=0 with certainty)\n- All perturbed trials use same amplitude distribution (unrealistic, discontinuous)\n- For curl fields, binary switch insufficient to stabilize oscillations\n\n### PAI-ASF (Probabilistic Adaptive Input — Active Scale Factor) — BEST OF THREE\n\nSISU = beta ~ U[0,1], scaling the perturbation: w = beta * sigma * epsilon where epsilon is base realization. Network knows \"how uncertain to be\" but not \"what the perturbation is.\"\n\nStrengths: prevents feedforward cancellation, graded signal, both magnitude and occurrence unpredictable, most analogous to human situation.\n\n## Shared Limitations (All Three Methods)\n\n1. Expected-cost optimization is LQG-like, not H-infinity-like. Backprop minimizes E[L], producing stochastic-optimal controllers, not minimax-optimal. Deepest structural issue.\n\n2. No penalty for fragility. Loss doesn't penalize sensitivity to perturbations.\n\n3. Backprop finds easiest solution. If partial adaptation reduces expected loss more efficiently than robustness, gradients push toward adaptation.\n\n4. Even PAI-ASF may learn \"adaptive gain scheduling\" (scaling effort with beta) rather than genuinely changing the control strategy.\n\n## The Peak Velocity Problem\n\nPAI-ASF networks don't show increased peak velocities at high SISU — a key H-infinity prediction confirmed in humans.\n\nOpus: primarily a loss function issue. Current time-windowed loss doesn't incentivize faster movements. H-infinity velocity increase requires accumulating running cost. LQG separation principle: trajectory shape independent of noise statistics.\n\nGemini (DISAGREES): partially structural. For curl fields, F = c*B*v means perturbation force is proportional to velocity. Higher peak velocities exponentially increase directional error cost. Gradient descent naturally finds low-velocity paths. This is structural for velocity-dependent perturbations, not just a loss weight.\n\nSynthesis: both factors contribute. Loss structure is dominant for velocity-independent perturbations (constant fields, gusts). Curl-field dynamics additionally suppress velocity.\n\n## H-infinity Framing Limitations\n\n- Applies to LTI systems; arm dynamics and curl fields are nonlinear\n- Static controller; real motor control adjusts gamma dynamically\n- Scalar gamma may be insufficient (mu-synthesis more appropriate)\n- Does not capture state-dependent perturbations\n\nAdditional frameworks worth considering:\n- Risk-sensitive control (Whittle 1981): LEQG bridges H2 and H-infinity\n- SISU as \"precision\" signal (Active Inference framing)\n\n## References\n\n- Crevecoeur, Cluff, \u0026 Scott (2019) J Neurosci 39(41): 8135-8148\n- Crevecoeur \u0026 Scott (2013) PLoS Comp Bio\n- Bian, Wolpert, \u0026 Jiang (2020) Neural Computation 32(3): 562-595\n- Izawa \u0026 Shadmehr (2014) Frontiers Comp Neurosci\n- Long et al. (2024) Learning H-Infinity Locomotion Control\n- Whittle (1981) Risk-sensitive optimal control\n\nCo-authored-by: Claude Opus 4.6 \u003cnoreply@anthropic.com\u003e, Gemini 3.1 Pro Preview \u003cnoreply@google.com\u003e","files":null}]}